docs.lead_paragraph: Nissan Motors filed a lawsuit in Japan on Wednesday seeking $90 million from its former chairman Carlos Ghosn, who fled the country before his trial on charges of financial wrongdoing.

headline.main: Nissan Sues Carlos Ghosn for $90 Million

docs.abstract: A new report points to a shortage of successful programs for tech careers. One, it says, shows how they can work.

docs.lead_paragraph: Tech jobs are coming to New York City in droves. All the big tech companies — even Amazon, which abandoned plans for a headquarters-style campus a year ago — are expanding in the city.

headline.main: New Yorkers Face a Training Gap for Tech Jobs, but a Study Finds Hope
headline.print_headline: Tech Jobs Are Flocking to New York. Can Workers Snare Them?

docs.abstract: Developers are offering a physical twist to keep traditional fans interested and draw new ones who are bored with their workouts.

docs.lead_paragraph: Tiffany Ruiz had tried various gyms, apps, workout routines and diets, all in an effort to get fit and lose some weight. “None of them worked because none of them kept my interest,” she said.

headline.main: Video Game Makers Want to Get Players Off the Couch

docs.abstract: Where couples start “living apart together,” for instance, can make a big difference if they divorce. State laws can also affect trusts and other financial transactions.

docs.abstract: Battling a troubled move and loss of shoppers’ trust, the New York online grocery service now contends with increased competition.
docs.snippet: Battling a troubled move and loss of shoppers’ trust, the New York online grocery service now contends with increased competition.
docs.lead_paragraph: About a year and a half ago, longtime patrons of the pioneering grocery delivery service FreshDirect started complaining that orders were arriving hours late. There were broken eggs and spoiled fruit. One customer reported that she had paid $200 for groceries — only to receive nothing but seltzer and a loaf of bread.

headline.main: FreshDirect, After Broken Eggs and Angry Customers, Stages a Comeback
headline.print_headline: Can FreshDirect Reclaim Ground Lost to Amazon?

docs.abstract: The corporate home of The New Yorker, which reported on Harvey Weinstein and others who have used nondisclosure agreements to silence accusers, steps back from a common settlement tactic.

docs.lead_paragraph: Condé Nast, the publishing giant behind Vogue, The New Yorker and Vanity Fair, said on Friday that it would no longer use nondisclosure agreements for matters involving harassment and discrimination.

docs.abstract: A start-up known for providing free credit scores, Credit Karma is set to avoid the I.P.O. market and instead sell to an established financial firm.
docs.snippet: A start-up known for providing free credit scores, Credit Karma is set to avoid the I.P.O. market and instead sell to an established financial firm.
docs.lead_paragraph: Intuit, the home of TurboTax and Mint, is nearing a deal to buy Credit Karma, a start-up that grew to fame by offering consumers free access to their credit scores, for about $7 billion in cash and stock, two people briefed on the matter said on Sunday.

headline.main: Intuit Is Expected to Buy Credit Karma in $7 Billion Deal
headline.print_headline: A Big Fish In Fintech Swallowing A Start-Up
